english:
  title: A Memorial Offering to Master Yangchon, the Venerable Gwon
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Way knows no division between ancient and modern—it is illuminated through those who embody it. Yet those who illuminate the Way are not born in every age. Even in the Middle Kingdom, this is so; how much more in our remote corner of the world. Alas, only Yangchon was heaven's singular gift of virtue. With nature pure and complete, his learning ripened early. Warmth and respect, diligence and frugality—these were his only conduct. The subtle meanings of the Sage and Mencius, the precepts of the Chengs and Zhou—he quieted his mind and layered effort upon effort until no source remained unplumbed. His discourse on the Learning Charts and his refinements of ritual propriety opened the hidden depths and brought honor to the Sage's gate. In all his deeds he upheld the bonds of order; in his writings he illuminated the canonical records. His practice was upright—neither ease nor peril could sway him. His integrity was steadfast—neither beginning nor end could alter it.

    I recall that in the year of the Rooster, I first came to know you. We served together under the masters of the Woodcutter and the Shepherd, together hoping to become men of renown. Then came the year of the Horse—together we were banished to the southern wilderness. The rains and floods of Sangdang revealed heaven's will most clearly. When the year of the Boar arrived, together we journeyed to pay our respects to the High Emperor of Ming. The Emperor elevated our kingdom's rank and granted us audience; your words rang true and your logic was pure, so near the emperor's presence. Through your rectitude, the empire's suspicions were dispelled and our nation's fortune flourished. In the year of the Dragon, together we raised up our present sovereign. We bore our seal of merit and walked the halls of state. Throughout our lives our risings and fallings were as one. The benefits of mutual refinement brought joy to my heart each day.

    You were born six years after me, yet your understanding preceded my own. My hair has turned white, but yours remained dark—surely, I thought, you would yet accomplish great works and bring peace to the realm. How could I have foreseen? In a single night, you departed this world. The sovereign mourns; the people grieve. "Who now will answer the nation's doubts? Who will heal the realm's afflictions?" And what of me, dull and flawed—who will correct my faults? This meager cup of wine is small, but my sorrow knows no bounds. Alas, receive this humble offering.
  footnotes:
    - Yangchon (陽村) refers to Gwon Geun (權近, 1352–1409), a prominent Neo-Confucian scholar and statesman of early Joseon.
    - The 'Woodcutter and Shepherd' (樵牧) alludes to the recluse scholars Yi In-bok and Yi Saek, masters under whom Ha Ryun and Gwon Geun studied.
    - The cyclical years mentioned (Rooster, Horse, Boar, Dragon) correspond to 1369, 1390, 1395, and 1400 respectively, marking key moments in their shared lives.
    - The 'Middle Kingdom' (中國) refers to China; 'our remote corner' is a modest reference to Korea.
    - The poem shifts from praising Gwon Geun's character and learning to mourning his sudden death and lamenting the loss of his counsel to the state.
